"1270","1307":"1307","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cokayne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Cockayne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cockayne","meanings":["English (Midlands and Yorkshire): nickname for a dreamer, from Middle English <i>cokayne</i> ‘cloud-cuckooland’, the name of an imaginary paradise (Old French <i>(pays de) cocaigne</i>, from Middle Low German <i>kōkenje</i>, a diminutive of <i>kōke</i> ‘cake’, since in this land the houses were thought to be made of cake). It may also be a variant of   Cocking   or from the unflattering Middle English nickname <i>cokin</i> (Old French <i>coquin)</i> ‘disreputable person’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Cokayne was born in 1270, in Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de Cokayne of Ashbourne, was 30 and his mother, Alice de Dalbury, was 15. He had at least 1 son with Sarah De Mercaston. He died in 1323, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1270–1323":"1270–1323","1307–1325":"1307–1325","1275–1326":"1275–1326","1300–1369":"1300–1369","1240–1284":"1240–1284","1255–Femal